From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Phil.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I'm Georgie.

5
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
In countering an animal in its natural habitat is a magical experience.

6
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Have you ever seen an animal in the wild Georgie?

7
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.000
Yes, I have actually, I was on a walk and we saw a baby Badger.

8
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
It was on its own and it was really cute.

9
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:30.000
What about you, Phil?

10
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.000
Well, the most impressive one I've ever seen.

11
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:33.000
It's actually a whale.

12
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
I was driving by the coast in Patagonia and you could see them in the sea.

13
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Well, that sounds amazing. And funny you say that because whale watching has become popular in many coastal parts of the world.

14
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
But watching whales is very different from what humans used to do.

15
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Hunt and kill them for their oil and meat.

16
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.000
An activity known as Whaling.

17
00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:01.000
Last year, marked the 40th anniversary of the International Whaling Commission's global moratorium.

18
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
That's a temporary ban on the commercial killing of whales.

19
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:09.000
Although Japan, Iceland and Norway continue to hunt whales,

20
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.000
there's no doubt the ban has saved many whale species from extinction.

21
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:19.000
In this program, we'll discuss our past and present relationship with these giants of the ocean.

22
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:24.000
And as usual, we'll learn some useful new words and phrases too.

23
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Plus you'll find all the vocabulary for this episode along with a quiz and worksheet on our website.

24
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:32.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com.

25
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
But first, I have a question for you, Georgie.

26
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:43.000
You probably know that the world's largest whale is the blue whale growing up to 30 meters long.

27
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
But which whale species is the smallest?

28
00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:49.000
Is it a, the blue whale?

29
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.000
B, the vacator whale?

30
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.000
Or see the pig me right whale?

31
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Hmm, well, pig me makes me think small, so I'm going to go with sea.

32
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.000
The pig me right whale.

33
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.000
Okay, we'll find out later in the program.

34
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Humans have hunted whales for at least a thousand years,

35
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.000
starting with small groups of hunters in slow moving wooden boats.

36
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:18.000
Catching whales like this was often unsuccessful, especially big whales like blue and humpback whales,

37
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
which can swim up to 30 kilometers per hour.

38
00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:27.000
But all that changed in the late 1800s as Jane Peas of the South Georgia Heritage Trust

39
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:32.000
explained to BBC Radio for program Rare Earth.

40
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:38.000
Something happened in Norway in the late 1800s, a chap called Sven Boin, who was a whale.

41
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:43.000
He invented what we now know as the exploding harpoon.

42
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
And that was a turning point for the whale, the whale can stand a chance.

43
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:57.000
In 1870, a chap, that's an informal word for a man called Sven Boin, invented the exploding harpoon, a weapon for killing whales.

44
00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.000
This was a turning point.

45
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:08.000
The phrase turning point means a time when a situation starts to change, especially in a positive way, although sadly not in this case.

46
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:16.000
After this, the whales didn't stand a chance, meaning they had no chance of successfully avoiding the hunters.

47
00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:25.000
Foines exploding harpoon added to the invention of faster steam-powered boats, increased whaling massively throughout the 20th century,

48
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:32.000
so the point where over 3 million whales had been killed, and many species faced extinction.

49
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.000
By the 1970s, there were only a few great whales left.

50
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:45.000
An environmental group like Greenpeace started the Save the Whales campaign to make people aware of devastation in whale populations and the cruelty of whaling.

51
00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:53.000
It became popular to listen to the song of the whale, recordings of whales communicating at sea, which sounds something like this.

52
00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Whales

53
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:10.000
He is marine biologist Joe Roman, discussing the Save the Whales campaign with BBC Radio Falls Breath.

54
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.000
People started thinking about whales in different ways.

55
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:27.000
And then we have to give a shout out to activists groups like Greenpeace, who put their ribboats, they put their zodiacs in between Soviet, hunting vessels and sperm whales, and they were very good at media.

56
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Joe gives a shout out to Greenpeace activists for protecting whales.

57
00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:35.000
To give a shout out to someone, means to praise them in public.

58
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Videos and photos taken by Greenpeace changed public opinion about whaling.

59
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Joe says Greenpeace were good at media, meaning they skillfully used media outlets like TV and newspapers to convey their message to the public.

60
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:58.000
Many whale species are still endangered, and all whales still face danger from ocean acidification and plastic pollution.

61
00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:07.000
But the moratorium, that means the temporary suspension on hunting them, has lasted 40 years, and hopefully will help protect whales for decades more.

62
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Okay Phil, isn't it time you revealed the answer to your question?

63
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Okay, I asked you which was the smallest species of whale.

64
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
And I said the pig me right whale, didn't I?

65
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:26.000
You did. Unfortunately, the answer is actually the Vakita whale, which is about 1.5 meters long.

66
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Oh, so cute. Okay, let's recap the rest of the vocabulary we've learned.

67
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
A chap is an informal word for a man.

68
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:38.000
A turning point is when a situation starts to change, especially for the better.

69
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
If someone doesn't stand a chance, they have no chance of success.

70
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:46.000
To give a shout out to someone, means to publicly praise them.

71
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And finally, if you're good at media, you are skillful at using media outlets to convey a message to the public.

72
00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:01.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but remember, you can find worksheets, quizzes, and loads more resources to improve your English on our website.

73
